@phdthesis{Laing2002,
abstract = {During normal sleep and anaesthesia the human EEG displays transient signals known as spindles: a 7 to 16 Hz oscillation which waxes and wanes over a period of approximately 1 s. Spindle detection is useful in quantifying depth of anaesthesia, but time consuming if done by human expert, hence a method of automatic spindle detection would be useful. In this thesis EEG ﬁles of patients undergoing propofol anaesthesia were used to derive spectrograms. We develop a method of adjusting the background noise of the EEG spectrogram to best reveal the time–frequency properties of the spindles present. Once this was achieved a number of selection criteria were obtained from a spindle data set in order to detect the spindles. The spindle detection algorithm was then applied to a data set of EEG ﬁles of patients undergoing propofol anaesthesia. The results were then compared with the time of loss of consciousness which had been recorded within the ﬁles. The spindle detection algorithm showed a clear increase in the number of spindles detected after loss of consciousness occurred. It was found that the time–frequency characteristics for spindles had two components. Acoherent component (possibly harmonic) and a noise component. The noise component had time–frequency characteristics that resembled the EEG background noise during transition from consciousness to unconsciousness, but at a much faster time scale.},
